    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-05-30T14:16:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-05-30T14:16:00-05:00" n="563"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d563">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_FE1">FE</gloss> files, lot 55 D 338, “South Korean Attitude
                    Toward Armistice, May 1953”</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chief of Staff United States Army (<persName
                            corresp="#p_CGJL1" type="from">Collins</persName>) to the Commander in
                        Chief Far East (<persName corresp="#p_CGMW1" type="to"
                        >Clark</persName>)</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d563fn1">For the events leading to the drafting of this and
                        subsequent telegram <gloss target="#t_DA1">DA</gloss> 940242, see memorandum
                        for the record by <persName corresp="#p_EMGCD1">Eddleman</persName>, June 1,
                            <ref target="#pg_1126">p. 1126</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>emergency</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-05-30T15:16:00-04:00"
                            >May 30, 1953—3:16 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_DA1">DA</gloss> 940241. From <gloss target="#t_CSUSA1"
                        >CSUSA</gloss> for <gloss target="#t_CINCUNC1">CINCUNC</gloss> exclusive for
                        <persName corresp="#p_RMGCL1">General Clark</persName>. Pass to US
                    Ambassador, Pusan exclusive for Amb <persName corresp="#p_BEO1"
                        >Briggs</persName>. The following are joint State–Defense instructions: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>The President has authorized you and <persName corresp="#p_BEO1"
                                >Briggs</persName> to inform <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                                >Rhee</persName> that US is prepared immediately to undertake
                            negotiations for a mutual defense treaty with the <gloss
                                target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> along lines of Philippine and <gloss
                                target="#t_ANZUS1">ANZUS</gloss> treaties which insofar as the
                                <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> is concerned would cover the
                            area now or hereafter under the administrative control of the <gloss
                                target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>. Other aspects <pb facs="1157" n="1123"
                                xml:id="pg_1123"/> of the treaty would require amplification as the
                            negotiations progress. We are agreeable to negotiate either in Korea or
                            in Washington.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Our willingness to negotiate and enter into such a treaty is subject
                            to receiving the following assurances from <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                                >Rhee</persName>: <list>
                                <label>a.</label>
                                <item>The Korean Govt will refrain from opposition to and agitation
                                    against an armistice along the lines presently proposed by the
                                        <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> and use its influence to
                                    restrain the Korean population from engaging in such agitation
                                    and opposition.</item>
                                <label>b.</label>
                                <item>The <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> will cooperate in the
                                    implementation of an armistice agreement.</item>
                                <label>c.</label>
                                <item>The armed forces of the <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>
                                    will remain under operational control of <gloss
                                        target="#t_CINCUNC1">CINCUNC</gloss> until US and <gloss
                                        target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> mutually agree such
                                    arrangements no longer necessary.</item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Upon receipt of such firm assurances the US will be prepared
                            immediately to undertake formal negotiations.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>The <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> must understand that
                            conclusion of such a treaty is subject to US constitutional processes
                            requiring the advice and consent of the Senate. <gloss target="#t_ROK1"
                                >ROK</gloss> cooperation with the <gloss target="#t_UNC1"
                                >UNC</gloss> will undoubtedly be a major factor in the attitude of
                            the Senate toward ratification of any such treaty.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>Insofar as the armistice is concerned you can assure <persName
                                corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> that there will be no departure
                            from the principles set forth by the <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss>
                            Delegation at the 25 May meeting.</item>
                        <label>6.</label>
                        <item>In presenting this matter to <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                                >Rhee</persName> you should state that US continues to consider the
                            “Greater Sanctions Statement” by 16 members of the UN, including the US,
                            meets the actual security needs of the <gloss target="#t_ROK1"
                                >ROK</gloss>. If, however, <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                                >Rhee</persName> feels that a mutual defense treaty has greater
                            dignity and assures <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> status in future
                            developing Pacific security system, US is agreeable to enter into such
                            an arrangement in addition to issuance of the “Greater Sanctions
                            Statement.”</item>
                        <label>7.</label>
                        <item>Timing of approach to <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> is
                            left to your discretion.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
            </div>
